name: Catrinas
description: José Guadalupe Posada called this figure "La Calavera Garbancera", a skull that represented and made fun of those people in whom indigenous blood ran but felt European. In Posada's words, "Death is democratic, since at the end of the day, blond, dark, rich or poor, all people end up being skulls." This skull was not wearing clothes, only a hat; It was later Diego Rivera who portrayed her as we know her today. He painted her in elegant clothing, typical of a catrín: a well-dressed and adorned man. This was the typical image of the aristocracy of the late 19th and early 20th centuries. La Catrina was born from La Calavera Garbancera ”.
